definition.value: An alicyclic ketone that is oxocyclopentanone substituted at position 3 by a carboxy group.
A dicarboxylic acid monoester that is methyl succinate substituted at position 2 by a phenyl group.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (4-coumaroyl)acetic acid.
A flavanol that is 3,4-dihydro-2H-chromene which is substituted at positions 3, 4, 5, and 7 by hydroxy groups, and at position 2 by a 3,4,5-trihydroxyphenyl group.
A hydrochloride salt prepared from equimolar amounts of pazopanib and hydrochloric acid. Used for treatment of kidney cancer.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of pazopanib.

A pyrimidine that is 5-(pyrimidin-2-yl}amino-2-methylbenzenesulfonamide substituted at position 4 by a (2,3-dimethylindazol-6-yl)(methyl)amino group. Used as its hydrochloride salt for treatment of kidney cancer.
An acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of feruloylacetyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A type of tannin usually found in brown algae such as kelps and rockweeds. Unlike the hydrolysable or condensed tannins, these compounds are oligomers of phloroglucinol.

A pteridine that is the N-4-[1-(2,4-diaminopteridin-6-yl)pent-4-yn-2-yl]benzoyl derivative of L-glutamic acid. Used for treatment of Peripheral T-Cell Lymphoma, an aggressive form of non-Hodgkins lymphoma.
A hydroxyflavan  that is 3,4-dihydro-2H-chromene which is substituted at positions 3, 5, and 7 by hydroxy groups, and at position 2 by a 3,4,5-trihydroxyphenyl group.
A a gallocatechin that has (2S,3R)-configuration.

A hydrochloride obtained by combining telavancin and hydrochloric acid. The composition of the compound is telavancin.nHCl where n = 1-3. Used for treatment of adults with complicated skin and skin structure infections caused by bacteria.
A flavan-3,3',4',5,5',7-hexol that has (2S,3S)-configuration.

A glycopeptide that is vancomycin substituted at position N-3'' by a 2-(decylamino)ethyl group and at position C-29 by a (phosphonomethyl)aminomethyl group. Used as its hydrochloride salt for treatment of adults with complicated skin and skin structure infections caused by bacteria.
Any ketone that is 1,3-diphenylpropanone and its derivatives obtained by substitution.
A member of the class of dihydrochalcones that is acetophenone in which one of the hydrogens of the methyl group is replaced by a benzyl group.
An antagonist at any adenosine receptor.
Tyramine substituted at position 3 by a nitro group.

A phytoceramide that is hexadecasphinganine substituted at positions 4 and 15 by a hydroxy group and a methyl group, respectively, with the amino group having condensed with a fatty acid to form a primary amide.
A C-nitro compound that is phenylacetaldehyde substituted at positions 3 and 4 by nitro and hydroxy groups respectively.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of feruloylacetic acid.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of thiophene-2-carboxylic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Any organic heterotetracyclic compound that consists of a pyran ring fused onto a xanthone skeleton.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate, diphosphate and carboxy groups of (2Z)-4-carboxy-2-sulfanylbut-2-enoyl-CoA.

An inorganic sodium salt comprised of a diphosphate(4-) anion and four sodium(1+) cations. More commonly known as tetrasodium pyrophosphate, it finds much use in the food industry as an emulsifier and in dental hygiene as a calcium-chelating salt.
A thiophenecarboxylic acid in which the carboxy group is located at position 2.
An acyl-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of malonyl-CoA methyl ester; major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the 1-carboxy group of (2Z)-2-sulfanylpent-2-enedioic acid.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of malonic acid monomethyl ester.

A racemate consisting of equal amounts of (R,R)- and (S,S)-asenapine maleate. Used for the acute treatment of schizophrenia and acute treatment of manic or mixed episodes associated with bipolar I disorder with or without psychotic features.
A maleate salt obtained by combining equimolar amounts of (R,R)-asenapine and maleic acid.

A collagen cross-link formed between hydroxylysine and methionine residues involving a sulfilimine (-S=N-) bond. It has been identified as linking hydroxylysine-211 and methioine-93 of adjoining protomers in a collagen IV network.
A maleate salt obtained by combining equimolar amounts of (S,S)-asenapine and maleic acid.
A racemate consisting of equal amounts of (R,R)- and (S,S)-asenapine(1+)
A N-acetyl-D-glucosamine 1-phosphate that is 2-deoxy-D-glucopyranose 1-(dihydrogen phosphate) substituted by an acetamido group at position 2.
An amino-acid residue consisting of an L-lysine residue, to the epsilon amino group of which is attached a glycylglycine dipeptide through an isopeptide bond.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of (R,R)-asenapine, obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of (S,S)-asenapine, obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group.

A racemate consisting of equal amounts of (R,R)- and (S,S)-asenapine. Used as its maleate salt for the acute treatment of schizophrenia and acute treatment of manic or mixed episodes associated with bipolar I disorder with or without psychotic features.
An L-alpha-amino acid consisting of L-lysine, to the epsilon amino group of which is attached a glycylglycine dipeptide through an isopeptide bond.
An organic heterotetracyclic compound that is 2,3,3a,12b-tetrahydrodibenzo[2,3:6,7]oxepino[4,5-c]pyrrole bearing methyl and chloro substituents at positions 2 and 5 respectively.
A 5-chloro-2-methyl-2,3,3a,12b-tetrahydrodibenzo[2,3:6,7]oxepino[4,5-c]pyrrole in which both of the stereocentres have R configuration.
A 5-chloro-2-methyl-2,3,3a,12b-tetrahydrodibenzo[2,3:6,7]oxepino[4,5-c]pyrrole in which both of the stereocentres have S configuration.

The calcium salt of pitavastatin. Used for treatment of hypercholesterolemia (elevated levels of cholesterol in the blood) on patients unable to sufficiently lower their cholesterol levels by diet and exercise.
A carboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of all four carboxy groups and the protonation of both of the primary amino groups of selenodiglutathione. The major species at pH 7.3.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of pitavastatin, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A peptide anion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups as well as protonation of the glutamyl amino group of S-(2-hydroxyacyl)glutathione; major species at pH 7.3.
A hexacyclic triterpenoid that consists of oleanane substituted by hydroxy groups at 3beta, 16alpha and C-30 positions and an oxolane bridge across positions 13 and 28.
An N-acylglycine in which the acyl group is specified as 4-pyridylacetyl.
